Durban - In honor of the centenary of Nelson Mandela’s birth, the Denis Hurley Centre this week launched the “100 years, 100 days, 100 ways to help” initiative.

The initiative is a call for action to people from all walks of life, including corporates, to volunteer their time, skills and to donate goods in an attempt to transform Durban’s inner-city while celebrating Madiba’s legacy.AdChoicesADVERTISINGinRead invented by Teads

Professor Ela Gandhi, granddaughter of Mahatma Gandhi, was the guest of honor at the launch, hosted on Wednesday.

Commitment to the cause, humility, willingness and the ability to change were the lessons Gandhi shared - which she believes were important throughout Nelson Mandela’s struggle for freedom and his revolutionary leadership.

“I believe Comrade Mandela’s birthday is a day we (where we) should focus on the reality we live in everyday. The poverty, hopelessness, rejection, hunger and illness we see around us. How can we help change the lives of all these people so that we can all celebrate freedom?” said Gandhi.

Gandhi’s message to young people is to move from materialism to “generosity, empathy and compassion instead of being self centered.”

“We need to look at the community around us and begin to think about other people and their plight,“ said Gandhi.















